tr> </table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A lot of problems in finance come =
from fire sales and contagion, and a lot of regulation is organized around =
preventing them. Most classically, there is bankruptcy law: When a company =
runs into financial trouble, all of its creditors have an incentive to dema=
nd their money back and grab collateral to get paid back before everyone el=
se, but if they all do that then the company will collapse and there won=E2=
=80=99t be much value left for anyone. So bankruptcy law gives the company =
the ability to stall=C2=A0its creditors and pay them all back equally, whic=
h prevents a rushed fire sale and preserves more value for all of them.</p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This problem is even more acute in=C2=A0<em>ba=
nking </em>=E2=80=94=C2=A0when a bank is troubled, depositors will run to g=
et their deposits back =E2=80=94=C2=A0so there are things like deposit insu=
rance and the central bank=E2=80=99s lender-of-last-resort function, which =
are designed to prevent value-destroying runs on the bank.</p><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">More generally, in financial markets, there is a classic ba=
d cycle where:</p><ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; m=
argin: 16px 0;"> <li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A lot of firms all hold =
a lot of the same sort of asset.</li> <li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">One=
 firm runs into trouble and has to sell its assets.</li> <li style=3D"margi=
n-bottom: 5px;">This drives down the price of the asset.</li> <li style=3D"=
margin-bottom: 5px;">Now the=C2=A0<em>other=C2=A0</em>firms that own it are=
 in trouble, so <em>they=C2=A0</em>have to sell.</li> <li style=3D"margin-b=
ottom: 5px;">Etc.</li></ul><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is called =E2=
=80=9Ccontagion,=E2=80=9D and financial regulators think a lot about how to=
 manage it. Mostly they try to prevent it, trying to limit crowded position=
s and run-prone firms. But sometimes, when a crowded position=C2=A0<em>has=
=C2=A0</em>gone wrong, regulators step in to manage the fallout and limit c=
ontagion. The most famous modern=C2=A0case is probably <a href=3D"https://l=
inks.message.bloomberg.com/u/click=3F_t=3Df574328d4d0c4c359b90d8e49b10e21d&=
_m=3D5db5163c047645418c9546b29d1b9031&_e=3DxmDe_vbQREDANimhDFXPLksA-y5mEelt=
